        "content": "<p>Hi all, new to lean/mathlib (github handle @ClaytonKnittel).</p>\n<p>I noticed mathlib seems to be lacking coverage of prime powers for p &gt; 2. Mathlib/Data/Nat/Prime/Pow.lean only has pow_minFac. I have written some nice theorems around prime powers that I'd like to contribute (proofs omitted for brevity):</p>\n<div class=\"codehilite\" data-code-language=\"Lean4\"><pre><span></span><code><span class=\"kn\">def</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">PrimePowerExp</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">p</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">exp</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℕ</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">p</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">Prime</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∧</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">p</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">^</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">exp</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">n</span>\n<span class=\"kn\">def</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">PrimePower</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">p</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℕ</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∃</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">exp</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">PrimePowerExp</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">p</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">exp</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">n</span>\n<span class=\"kn\">def</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">IsPrimePower</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℕ</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∃</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">p</span><span class=\"o\">,</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">PrimePower</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">p</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">n</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">theorem</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">PrimePower</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">one_factor</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">p</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">e</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℕ</span><span class=\"o\">}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">n_ne_0</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">≠</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"mi\">0</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">p_prime</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">p</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">Prime</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"n\">PrimePowerExp</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">p</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">e</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">↔</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">factorization</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">=</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">single</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">p</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">e</span>\n\n<span class=\"kn\">theorem</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">PrimePower</span><span class=\"bp\">.</span><span class=\"n\">dvd_is_pp</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">{</span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">p</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">m</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">ℕ</span><span class=\"o\">}</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">hn</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">PrimePower</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">p</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"o\">)</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">(</span><span class=\"n\">h</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">m</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"bp\">∣</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">n</span><span class=\"o\">)</span>\n<span class=\"w\">    </span><span class=\"o\">:</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">PrimePower</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">p</span><span class=\"w\"> </span><span class=\"n\">m</span>\n</code></pre></div>\n<p>I'd appreciate any feedback on structure (e.g. the nested defs for prime powers is kinda annoying, but I don't want you to have to say <code>∃ e, PrimePowerExp p e n</code> everywhere you want a prime power when you don't care what <code>e</code> is). Thanks a bunch in advance!</p>",
